–Overleden","1187–1238":"1187–1238","1187":"1187","1220":"1220","1230":"1230","1274":"1274","1175":"1175","1252":"1252","1305":"1305","1238":"1238","1236":"1236","1301":"1301","1202":"1202","1289":"1289","1267":"1267","1255":"1255","1254":"1254","about 1255":"circa 1255","about 1254":"circa 1254","1318":"1318","about 1252":"circa 1252","Nottinghamshire, England":"Nottinghamshire, England","Markham Nottinghamshire England":"Nottinghamshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Markham Clinton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Markham Clinton, Nottinghamshire, England"},"en":{"1230–1289":"1230–1289","1202–1267":"1202–1267","1236–Male":"1236–Deceased","1238–Male":"1238–Deceased","1220–1274":"1220–1274","1252–1305":"1252–1305","1254–1318":"1254–1318","1255–1301":"1255–1301","1175–Male":"1175–Deceased","1187–1238":"1187–1238","1187":"1187","1220":"1220","1230":"1230","1274":"1274","1175":"1175","1252":"1252","1305":"1305","1238":"1238","1236":"1236","1301":"1301","1202":"1202","1289":"1289","1267":"1267","1255":"1255","1254":"1254","about 1255":"about 1255","about 1254":"about 1254","1318":"1318","about 1252":"about 1252","Nottinghamshire, England":"Nottinghamshire, England","Markham Nottinghamshire England":"Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","Markham Clinton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Markham Clinton, Nottinghamshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Markham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Markham Clinton or East Markham (Nottinghamshire). The placename derives from Old English <i>mearc</i> ‘mark, boundary’ + <i>hām</i> ‘village, homestead’ or <i>hamm</i> ‘water meadow’.","Irish: English surname used as an equivalent of Gaelic <b>Ó Marcacháin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Marcachán</i>’, a diminutive of <i>Marcach</i> ‘horseman, rider’ (see   Markey  ). This was originally a Galway surname but is now found mainly in Clare, sometimes translated into English as   Ryder  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Markey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Donal, Donovan, Fergal.","Irish (Monaghan): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Marcaigh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Marcach</i>’, a name meaning ‘horseman, knight’, from <i>marc</i> ‘horse’. Compare   Markham   2.","English: apparently from a placename meaning ‘boundary river’ in Old or Middle English, but no such place has been identified."]},{"name":"Markum","meanings":["Altered form of English   Markham  ."]},{"name":"Marcum","meanings":["Altered form of English   Markham  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert de Markham was born in 1230, in Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, William Markham, was 55 and his mother, Cecilia de Lexington, was 43. He married Sarah de Snitterton. They were the parents of at least 3 daughters. He died in 1289, in his hometown, at the age of 59."},"et":{"1230–1289":"1230–1289","1202–1267":"1202–1267","1236–Male":"1236–Surnud","1238–Male":"1238–Surnud","1220–1274":"1220–1274","1252–1305":"1252–1305","1254–1318":"1254–1318","1255–1301":"1255–1301","1175–Male":"1175–Surnud","1187–1238":"1187–1238","1187":"1187","1220":"1220","1230":"1230","1274":"1274","1175":"1175","1252":"1252","1305":"1305","1238":"1238","1236":"1236","1301":"1301","1202":"1202","1289":"1289","1267":"1267","1255":"1255","1254":"1254","about 1255":"umbes 1255","about 1254":"umbes 1254","1318":"1318","about 1252":"umbes 1252","Nottinghamshire, England":"Nottinghamshire, England","Markham Nottinghamshire England":"Nottinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Markham Clinton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Markham Clinton, Nottinghamshire, England"},"fi":{"1230–1289":"1230–1289","1202–1267":"1202–1267","1236–Male":"1236–Kuollut","1238–Male":"1238–Kuollut","1220–1274":"1220–1274","1252–1305":"1252–1305","1254–1318":"1254–1318","1255–1301":"1255–1301","1175–Male":"1175–Kuollut","1187–1238":"1187–1238","1187":"1187","1220":"1220","1230":"1230","1274":"1274","1175":"1175","1252":"1252","1305":"1305","1238":"1238","1236":"1236","1301":"1301","1202":"1202","1289":"1289","1267":"1267","1255":"1255","1254":"1254","about 1255":"noin 1255","about 1254":"noin 1254","1318":"1318","about 1252":"noin 1252","Nottinghamshire, England":"Nottinghamshire, England","Markham Nottinghamshire England":"N